  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  // TRANSLATION GUIDE — Read before translating
  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  //
  // RULE 1: Placeholders are SACRED. Never translate, rename, reorder, or
  //         duplicate them. Copy them character-for-character into the
  //         translated string. They look like:
  //
  //           %1$s   %1$d   %1$.1f     — numbered format placeholders
  //           $variableName             — Kotlin string templates
  //           ${expression}             — Kotlin expression templates
  //
  //   WRONG:  "Como devo me ajustar para \"%1$s\"s?"   (added trailing "s")
  //   RIGHT:  "Como devo me ajustar para \"%1$s\"?"
  //
  //   WRONG:  "Peso: ${scaleUnit.uppercase()} kg"
  //   RIGHT:  "Peso: ${scaleUnit.uppercase()}"
  //
  // RULE 2: Emojis are part of the source. Keep them in the same position
  //         relative to the text. Don't add new emojis. Don't remove them.
  //
  //           ** Suggest a protein snack
  //           ** Sugiera um lanche proteico
  //
  // RULE 3: Punctuation and formatting marks (•, —, „", %, etc.) should
  //         follow the conventions of the target language.
  //
  // RULE 4: Keep the same tone and brevity. UI labels are short. Suggestion
  //         chips are casual. Notifications are concise.
  //
  // RULE 5: Do NOT translate keys (the left side). Only translate values
  //         (the right side).
  //
  // RULE 6: Keys ending in _fmt use printf-style formatting. The format
  //         specifiers (%1$d, %1$s, %1$.1f) must remain unchanged.
  //
  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

